Use Matplotlib on historical stock prices to Visualize¶

i also import Matplotlib as we will use it to visualize my findings. The matplotlib is important to tell Jupyter notebook how to visualize the results from our plots.

In [20]:
import pandas_datareader.data as web
bbni = web.DataReader('BBNI.JK', 'yahoo', start='2012-01-01', end='2022-01-01')
bbni
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib notebook
In [21]:
bbni.rename(columns={'Adj Close': 'Price'}, inplace=True)

A simple plot can now be done as follows.

In [22]:
bbni.plot()
Out[22]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Date'>

Another way to use Matplotlib is in an objective way.

In [23]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
bbni['Price'].plot(ax=ax)
ax.set_ylabel("Price")
ax.set_title("BBNI")
Out[23]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'BBNI')

Next, I will try to make a plot with multiple axes in one figures

The plt.subplots(2, 2) creates a 2-by-2 grid of axis. I access the axis in x by ax[0, 0] and similar for other axis.

In [24]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 2)
bbni['Open'].plot(ax=ax[0, 0], title="Open")
bbni['High'].plot(ax=ax[0, 1], title="High")
bbni['Low'].plot(ax=ax[1, 0], title="Low")
bbni['Price'].plot(ax=ax[1, 1], title="Price")
plt.tight_layout()

A bar plot can be created as follows, where i also make a time interval of the data i want by using .loc[].

In [25]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
bbni['Volume'].loc['2020-07-01':'2020-08-15'].plot.barh(ax=ax)
Out[25]:
<AxesSubplot:ylabel='Date'>
